bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Thomas Hahn (1926- 2007) was a professional industrial archaeologist, a college professor and a bona fide Indian medicine man. He was born in November 1926, in Topeka, Kansas. After retiring from the Navy following a 28 year career, Hahn earned several degrees including a Masters degree in History and a PhD in Industrial Archeology. He spoke five language and was closely connected with his Native American heritage and at one point in his life served as Chief of the Kansas Delawares Nation.

Hahn had a 28-year career in the Navy that spanned three wars, beginning in 1944 as a seaman second class and ended in retirement in 1972 with a captain's rank. He wrote 30 volumes on the C&O Canal for the National Park Service, as well as historical books, essays and brochures.

He was considered one of the world's foremost expert on the C&O Canal. He was the field archaeologist on two major canal restoration projects; one in Havre de Grace, Md., the other in Alexandria, Va. Hahn founded national and international canal societies as a way of sharing information. He was president and founder of the 25-member Eastern West Virginia Archeology Society and served as president of the American Canal Association from 1972-97.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This Collection contains materials related to Thomas Hahn's involvement in the C&O Canal Association, as well as other canals related to the C&O, and canals in general.

A large part of the collection consists of photographic negatives, slides and prints of the C&O Canal. Most of these photographs, negatives, and slides relate to illustrations in publications that he authored or co-authored. Other items include reference material for his books, correspondence, and maps.
Please note: many of the images, especially those in boxes 21-25, are not in order and may require additional time to use for research.
The collection covers the years from 1939-1993 and is housed in 31 boxes, or approximately 10 linear feet.

An immigrant boat. Passage $5.00 - Philadelphia to Pittsburgh - without meals. Local residents would throw stones and try to prevent boat from stopping over. They thought the immigrants carried disease. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
Aqueduct and tunnel at Tunnelton, PA (West end of tunnel). Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Wharves were built at loading points along the canal, but always on the berm side opposite the Towpath. In spots without a wharf, where the boats could not be brought to the edge of the water, a plank was run ashore for picking up passengers or freight. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Inclined Plane #4. This is a view looking west towards Lilly. The length of the plane was 2194 feet and rose 187 feet. Today this is a highway route from Lilly to Cresson. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The arrival of a passenger train at the head of a plane. The machinery for raising the train to the top of the plane is located underneath the building. At Plane #8 the remains of a Heist House foundation can be seen today. This was the longest plane -3116 ft. - and rose 307 ft. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

A 'sectional boat' at Penn Lock at Harrisonburg. It was here that the corner stone was laid for the first lock on March 14 1827. Ground had been broken door the canal on July 4, 1826. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The Summit House near Plane #5. This was also a famous stopping place on the APRR. The building is still in use (1966). U.S. Route 22 passes directly in front of the Summit House. The Hotel Register is preserved at the Baker Mansion, the headquarters of the Blair County Historical Society. It contains many interesting entries. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
A scene at the head of the planes. Since there is an inn nearby it must be on the western slope of the mountain. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The Allegheny Portage Railroad along the Conemaugh Gorge. This was also known as the long level - 13 miles. Charles Dickens gives a vivid description of this section in his American Notes. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
A stop along the route at a nearby inn. This was in the early days before locomotives were used. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The junction of the Philadelphia & Columbia railroad and the Pennsylvania Canal at Columbia. An inclined plane was also located in this area. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Hitching a section boat to the cable so that it may be hauled to the top of the plane. This is the foot of Plane #8 and the stone culvert shown in this drawing is still visible today. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
A Packet Boat passing a freight boat. Packets had the right-of-way. Scene is near the Packsaddle in the Blairsville area. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
A delay caused by a break in the canal. Many of the passengers took advantage of this to visit nearby inns and to see the country side. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
Many of the communities along the canal were centers of boat-building. This scene is near Blairsville. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
The Dauphin Narrows north of Harrisonburg on the Eastern Division of the canal. Note that the telegraph was in use at the time. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The American House - one of the more important hotels of the Canal Era. Located in Johnstown, it was built and in use before 1840. It was not damaged by the floods of 1889 and 1936 and it is still in use - though its glory has long since passed. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Not all locks on the canal were used to raise and lower boats. The one shown here is a control lock for controlling the level of the water in the canal. Dauphin- 1 mile south. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

When the navigation season ended due to the canal freezing, many of the boat owners lived in their boats. The warehouses were filled with merchandise to be hauled after the first thaw. The frozen canal provided great pleasure for the children. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Water was raised by bucket from the canal for those fastidious enough to want to wash up. Drinking water was kept in a barrel filled from wells along the way. A metal dipper held by a chain served all. Whiskey was sold on most boats for those unable to drink water. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
The 'canalers' were a tough lot and fights were common. They fought for position at the canal locks and with the town bullies. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

A freight boat leaving a lock. The packet boat will soon be in the lock and then on its way east. This scene is on the Juniata Division. It is reported that it took four minutes for a boat to pass through a lock. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The end of a stretch of slack water navigation in the Pack Saddle. The boat will soon be in the lock and on its way to Pittsburgh. This drawing was made from a photograph taken in the 1870's. The Pennsylvania Railroad is on the right - at the top of the hill. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
The many types of boats used on the Pa. Canal. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

A 'Winding Bridge' - given this name because the mules wound their way over the bridge. This was necessary when the towpath changed from one side of the canal to the other. It was done without unhitching. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
The Mountain House at Hollidaysburg. This was one of the more famous inns along the canal and was located near the Basin. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The Safety car. An invention of one of the early engineers on the APRR. If the cable broke (and it often did) the loaded car would be stopped by the weight applied to the safety car. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The flag signaling system used at many of the planes to indicate how many passengers wanted to order dinner at the next inn. The flag was raised once for each five diners. Final instructions were sent by a boy on horseback to the innkeeper. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

A Towpath Bridge. This was also used when the towpath crossed from one side to the other - similar to slide 263 (number on slide). However, this bridge was for road traffic also. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

At 6:00 AM the sleeping shelves were removed and tables assembled for the serving of breakfast. From 12 to 36 passengers sat down for the meals. Food was placed on table in big platters, each passenger helping himself. Dickens cites elaborate menus - tea, coffee, bread, butter, salmon, shad, liver, steak, potatoes, pickles, ham, and chop black puddings, sausages. The cook was usually a free Negro. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The arrival of the first boat. In many communities this called for a celebration...as reported in the newspapers of towns along the Juniata Division. Parade with flag. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The Aqueduct at Newport. The design is very similar to others along the canal. However, the timbers were probably used as shoring when a weakness developed. Cast iron plates were also reported to be used. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The Skew Arch. Incline Plane #6 went through the arch and the Huntington, Indiana Turnpike went over it. It is well preserved today and is part of a small park. The National Historical Site will include this area. The wedge driver is shown in this drawing - he drove the wedges daily to keep the rails in the chairs. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
The Basin at Hollidaysburg. Note the passengers leaving the packet boat to board the train for the trip over the mountain to Johnstown. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Foot of the Belmont plane near Philadelphia. It was here that a locomotive took over when the engine in the hoist house failed, proving that locomotives could be used on steep grades. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

"Low Bridge" - everybody down. This call was necessary when the canal boat passed under a bridge. Dickens gives a good description of the actions of the steerman and the passengers in his American Notes. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Traveling through the tunnel at Tunnelton. There were two tunnels on the Western Division. Shortly after this tunnel was built it had to be lined with brick as it continued to have rock falls. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The stone ties, chairs and rail as used on the Portage Railroad. The stone ties were 2' x 2' and 18 inches high with two holes drilled and plugged. They cost $.53 each and weighed 600 to 700 pounds. The chairs weighed 13 lbs. While the rails weighed 42 lbs. Per yard. The early rails were rolled in England. Later they were made in Pennsylvania. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
The Lift Lock below the double lock at Millerstown. In the distance can be seen the rope ferry and the double lock. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

This illustrates the type of construction on the various incline planes of the A.P.R.R. The information is from the reports of Sylvester Welsh, employed by the Canal Commissioners as "Principal Engineer." Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The canal was built by human sweat! The pick, shovel and wheel barrow were the tools used. Plows and scrapers were also used. Yet the canal was completed in good time. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Trouble! Cars had difficulty making the short radius turnouts on Basin St. (Later called Railroad St.) to warehouses. Story in History of Cabris County says "Track turnouts were designed for the short 4 wheel cars. Later the 8 wheel cars had difficulty in making the turnouts." On the Main Portage Railroad 442 feet was the minimum radius, but most curves exceeded 950 ft. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
Viaduct across the Beaverton at Hollidaysburg. Similar in design to the Ebensburg Viaduct (Slide No. 290). Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

When opened the Columbia and Philadelphia railroad consisted only of the state built and operated trackage. The cars were operated by individuals and private companies. Private operation of the rolling stock created so much confusion and difficulties that the state soon took over complete operation of the road and replaced horses with steam locomotives which were then being developed. Very ornate stagecoach type car and horses. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Human muscle moved boats in Johnstown Basin: 2 men with 20ft. long poles. Sometimes there were as many as 30 boats in the Basin at one time. Barrels were much in use, since many commodities were easily shipped in barrels which were made in large quantities. Every village was likely to have a cooper. Remember when crackers came in a barrel? Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

The state was finding that the process of taking section boats apart placing them in and out of the water was a burdensome process. The state developed a new type of boat, Car Box Boat that would carry about 10 sealed boxes. The boxes could be transferred by crane to Portage cars without breaking seals could carry greater tonnage with cheaper handling. In recent years the Pennsylvania Railroad used the same system. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
Diagram of Hoist Engine originally designed by Edward Miller and built in Pittsburgh 1832. Reconstructed from written records. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Villages grew along the Portage railroad where trains were likely to stop (wood or coaling stations or water) permitting passengers to get a meal (a drink could be gotten also). Lilly, Portage, Half Way House a Summerhill, Cresson, Wilmore, Settlements near Johnstown or Hollidayburg not likely to have inns. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

All aboard! Blairsville and points west through to Pittsburgh. One or two boats per day usually left in the morning. Most passengers spent the previous night in hotels, there were about a dozen in Johnstown. Portage railroad did not run at night. Passengers from arriving boats could go aboard trains. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Unloading Borden Car at warehouse. Some days as many as 30 boats waiting for loading or unloading. A busy place, in summer manual labor in demand. In winter little work available except for repair work in State Shop. The many hotels (about a dozen) surrounding the Basin catered to passengers and local workers. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Boats over the mountains, Astonishing! Hauling section boat to Johnstown crossing the Ebensburg Viaduct (at Wilmore) 40 ft. span Semi elliptical arch 10' rise, 27 ft. from rail to water. Width of Viaduct 25' 10" (for two tracks). Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

This diagram based on written descriptions by S. Welch, Chief Engineer of the project. The excavations at the Lemon House by Temple University summer of 1968 may make some changes necessary. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Picking up freight along the line. A turnout for loading and unloading at a village. The Portage opened backwoods mountain area to an outlet for their farm and other products. Before the Portage the best way to ship their wheat and corn was as whiskey. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Explosion of Engine Bushhill April 23, 19=847. On the 13 mile level (2) mile east of the tunnel force of stream turned engine over and backwards crushing tender and freight car against dome. Engineer James Patterson killed, two others badly hurt. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Fog in mountain valleys slowed travel rate. It interfered with operation of planes also. Sometimes in early October or late April snow would create a similar scene, except for foliage and snow on the ground. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Boiler Room from reports of S. Welch: At Plane #8 3,116 ft. long (plane operation 352 ft./min.) takes 9 min. to move cars bottom to top requires 60 gals. of water as steam burns about 6# coal per min. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Building based on several of paintings at Head Houses. Machinery on Mr. Welch's reports: 2 engines but only one used, other is a spare. Same arrangement for boilers but had probably a connection to permit any boiler with either engine. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E

Big Wheels at head of planes each 8 ft. diameter. Horizontal sheave 9'7" diameter. 22 "- 3" diameter ropes. One engine on each side but only one engine operates, other is a spare Clutch couplings connect either. Horizontal sheave can drift 15ft. to take up slack and keep rope taut moved by weight hanging in pit. Allegheny Portage Railroad slides drawing by P.J. Hoffman P.E
